WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.340
JOEL LEWIS: Hi.

00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:14.140
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:14.140 --> 00:00:16.870
In lecture, you've been doing
related rates problems. I've

00:00:16.870 --> 00:00:18.910
got another example
for you, here.

00:00:18.910 --> 00:00:20.585
So this one's a really
tricky one.

00:00:20.585 --> 00:00:22.690
So I'm going to give you some
time to work on it.

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:25.730
But I really think you
should try and work

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:26.910
through this one yourself.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:28.280
It'll be well worth
your effort.

00:00:30.820 --> 00:00:32.810
So we've got here, OK so
this is a mouthful.

00:00:32.810 --> 00:00:36.360
We've got a 20 foot long
ladder and it's leaning

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:38.400
against a 12 foot wall.

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.870
But it's leaning
over the wall.

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:43.010
So 5 feet of the ladder
project over

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:44.530
the top of the wall.

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:47.480
And then the bottom of the
ladder is being pulled away

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:50.840
from the wall at 5
feet per second.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:55.040
The question is, while this is
going on, how quickly is the

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:57.240
top of the ladder
going downwards?

00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:59.310
How quickly is it approaching
the ground?

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:01.750
So why don't you take
a few minutes.

00:01:01.750 --> 00:01:03.260
Well, maybe more than
a few for this one.

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:06.150
It took me a while to work
it out the first time.

00:01:06.150 --> 00:01:09.410
Take a few minutes, work this
one out, come back, and we'll

00:01:09.410 --> 00:01:10.660
see how it went.

00:01:19.070 --> 00:01:19.480
All right.

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:22.230
So hopefully you've had some
luck working out this problem

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:22.760
on your own.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.040
Now let's work it
out together.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:29.940
So OK, so this is a sort of
classic, really tricky related

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:32.990
rates problem in that there's
a lot of geometric work that

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:34.560
you have to do at
the beginning in

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:36.110
order to get this right.

00:01:36.110 --> 00:01:40.210
And then once you get the
geometry down, the calculus is

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:42.930
basically totally straight
forward.

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:44.920
You know, you compute a couple
derivatives, you use the chain

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:45.486
rule once, whatever.

00:01:45.486 --> 00:01:46.736
You know.

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:50.180
So OK, so let's start
off by trying and

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:51.890
drawing a careful picture.

00:01:51.890 --> 00:01:54.090
And then we'll have to figure
out what the quantities that

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:55.910
we're interested in are and the

00:01:55.910 --> 00:01:59.330
relationships between them.

00:01:59.330 --> 00:02:01.810
So we have here, here's
the ground.

00:02:01.810 --> 00:02:09.520
And we have a 12 foot wall.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:14.120
And we have a 20 foot ladder
leaning against the wall and

00:02:14.120 --> 00:02:15.490
extending over it.

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:18.170
So my ladder.

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:24.700
So here's my ladder.

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:30.000
Here's my wall.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:30.480
All right.

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:36.820
And this, the bottom of the
ladder here, is what's getting

00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:42.090
pulled away from the wall
at 5 units per second.

00:02:42.090 --> 00:02:43.760
5 feet per second.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:51.670
So 5 feet per second is
how fast that's going.

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:53.340
And we're interested, so while
you do that, you know, the

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:54.540
ladder is changing position.

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:59.010
So the question is, how fast
is the top of the ladder

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:00.100
descending?

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.130
So you know, it might also
be moving in some other

00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:04.370
directions, but we're just
interested in how quickly it's

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:07.230
going straight down.

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:08.620
So OK, so first, let's
talk about the

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:09.610
things that don't change.

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:12.220
So the height of this wall
is not changing.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:14.430
The wall is staying put
the whole time.

00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:16.380
And the length of the ladder
is not changing.

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:20.550
That's staying put, as well.

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:21.520
But what, OK, so those
are the fixed

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.790
qualities in this problem.

00:03:22.790 --> 00:03:25.600
Basically, everything
else is changing.

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:31.210
So for example, this distance
between the base of the wall

00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:33.890
and the base of the ladder,
that's changing because the

00:03:33.890 --> 00:03:35.610
ladder is being pulled
away from the wall.

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:37.230
So we can give that a name.

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:40.670
Lat's call that, that's a
horizontal distance, so we can

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:42.840
call that x, say.

00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:49.480
And the height of the top of
the ladder is changing, so

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:52.460
let's draw that in.

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:53.930
That's what we're
interested in.

00:03:53.930 --> 00:03:57.090
It's the height, so
we can call tit y.

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:58.200
And let's see.

00:03:58.200 --> 00:03:58.910
What else?

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:02.550
Well OK, the whole ladder isn't
changing in length, but

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:06.630
the amount, but as this gets
pulled, you know, this top

00:04:06.630 --> 00:04:09.690
point is sort of sliding down
towards the wall, the amount

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:14.070
of the ladder that extends over
the wall is changing.

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:15.180
So I guess we could choose.

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:18.130
We could give this a variable
name or we could give this

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:19.130
part a variable name.

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:22.646
I think I'm going to give the
little one a variable name.

00:04:22.646 --> 00:04:26.630
I'll call it d for distance,
I guess.

00:04:26.630 --> 00:04:28.130
And OK so this is d
because the whole

00:04:28.130 --> 00:04:30.430
ladder has length, 20.

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:38.930
We have that this part, this
segment has length 20 minus d.

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:43.180
Ok so, I think that those
quantities describe all the

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:47.810
possible lengths of interest
in this picture.

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:48.020
So now, OK.

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:50.850
So that's just the first,
the set up.

00:04:50.850 --> 00:04:52.860
That's the first thing
that has to happen.

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:55.970
Now after we set up, we need
to figure out what the

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:58.170
relationships between these
different variables are.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:03.670
Well, let's see.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:04.440
What have we got?

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.520
Well one thing we've got is
that we've got a right

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:09.030
triangle here.

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:14.200
So the wall and the ground
and the ladder.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.535
Those three segments form
a right triangle.

00:05:16.535 --> 00:05:18.060
So OK.

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:20.530
So we can apply the Pythagorean
Theorem here.

00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:23.100
So that's one relationship we
have, and that's going to give

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.700
us a relationship between x
and well, OK, 20 minus d.

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:31.390
So that'll give us a
relationship between x and d.

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:33.390
So this, so OK, so what does the
Pythagorean Theorem say?

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:40.810
So by the Pythagorean Theorem,
we have x squared plus--

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:41.770
that's a 1--

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:49.580
12 squared is equal the to
quantity 20 minus d squared.

00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:53.600
So that's one identity that we
have, identity we have that

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.620
relates these three
quantities.

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:57.550
And so that's good.

00:05:57.550 --> 00:06:00.340
Because we know how fast
x is changing.

00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:05.500
And so with this identity, that
means we can use related

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:09.310
rates to figure out how fast
d is changing, as well.

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:10.130
So that's good.

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:12.240
That'll be a step in the right
direction, but what we

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:15.017
actually need to know is
how fast y is changing.

00:06:15.017 --> 00:06:18.180
So right?

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.330
Because that's what the question
is asking for-- how

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:22.320
quickly is the top of the ladder
approaching the ground?

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:25.190
So how, what's the rate
of change in y

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:27.220
with respect to time?

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:32.190
So I need another identity here
in order to figure out

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:36.620
what the relationship with y is
and these other variables.

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:38.380
And there are a couple
of different

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:39.640
ways to go about this.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:42.610
I think the one that I'm going
to do-- so there is another

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:43.900
right triangle here.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:48.740
So you could, if you wanted to
name this segment, as well,

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:51.870
then you could do another
right triangle.

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:53.970
But then you'd need a third
relationship relating this

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:56.450
segment to d or something
like that.

00:06:56.450 --> 00:06:58.730
So I'm not going to go that
route, but I'm going to go do

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:00.830
something related to that,
which is that this bigger

00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:06.640
right triangle, right, which has
the height of the top of

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:09.940
the ladder from the ground and
the whole length of the ladder

00:07:09.940 --> 00:07:13.820
as two of its sides, and a piece
of the ground, so that

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:16.050
bigger right triangle
is similar to this

00:07:16.050 --> 00:07:16.785
smaller right triangle.

00:07:16.785 --> 00:07:17.990
Right?

00:07:17.990 --> 00:07:20.070
I mean, they have, they're right
triangles and they have

00:07:20.070 --> 00:07:21.930
the same base angle there.

00:07:21.930 --> 00:07:25.150
So they're similar triangles.

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:27.900
So OK, so by similar triangles--
now I have to

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:29.420
remember all my geometry,
right?

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:33.960
So the ratio of corresponding
sides are equal, so in this

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:37.760
case, the ratio of the
hypotenuses is equal to the

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:40.640
ratio of these legs.

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:41.970
And that'll relate.

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:46.340
So the hypotenuses involve d and
the vertical legs, well,

00:07:46.340 --> 00:07:48.430
one of them is just constant
and one of them involves y.

00:07:48.430 --> 00:07:51.000
So that'll set up a relationship
between d and y,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.260
and so then I'll have x
linked to d and I'll

00:07:53.260 --> 00:07:54.560
have d linked to y.

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:56.650
And so then we can use related
rates to figure out what the

00:07:56.650 --> 00:08:00.420
relationship between y and x
is and figure out the thing

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:03.990
we're after, which is the
rate of change in y.

00:08:03.990 --> 00:08:05.725
So OK, so I haven't actually
written anything down, yet.

00:08:05.725 --> 00:08:08.660
So what is the similar
triangle?

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:11.930
So here,et's look at
the hypotenuses.

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:18.880
So the big hypotenuse has
length 20, and the small

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:25.440
hypotenuse has length
20 minus d.

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:25.890
Good.

00:08:25.890 --> 00:08:29.190
So that's the ratio of the
hypotenuses, and so that has

00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:32.420
to be equal to the ratio of
the corresponding legs.

00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:40.700
And so the big leg is y, and
the small leg is 12.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:41.950
OK.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:44.710
All right, so there's
Pythagorean Theorem.

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:45.970
There's similar triangles.

00:08:45.970 --> 00:08:49.020
So we now have the relationships
that we're after

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:52.880
relating x and y and d
all to each other.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:55.250
Great.

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:59.245
So now we can do the calculus
part of this problem, right?

00:09:04.270 --> 00:09:05.010
So now we know, oh, I
guess, actually, we

00:09:05.010 --> 00:09:06.330
need a few more things.

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:06.696
Take it back.

00:09:06.696 --> 00:09:12.120
So now we need, we're after, as
I said, a particular moment

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:15.310
in time, and at our particular
moment in time, so I haven't

00:09:15.310 --> 00:09:18.510
used this one given, yet, that
5 feet of the wall--

00:09:18.510 --> 00:09:18.910
oh, sorry--

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:20.885
5 feet of the ladder projects
over the wall.

00:09:20.885 --> 00:09:35.990
So OK, so at our moment, so at
the key moment, we have that d

00:09:35.990 --> 00:09:37.850
is equal to 5.

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:48.490
OK, so that means 20 minus
d is equal to 15.

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:49.460
What else does that mean?

00:09:49.460 --> 00:09:53.270
So that means that at that
moment, x in this right

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:57.790
triangle is the third leg in a
right triangle with hypotenuse

00:09:57.790 --> 00:09:59.410
15 and one leg 12.

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:01.930
So that's one of your three,
four, five triangles, but

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:03.150
blown up a little bit.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:08.870
So we have at that moment,
that x is equal to 9.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:11.350
And OK, so at that moment, to
figure out y, we can use this

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:16.810
other relationship that we have.
So 20 over 15 is equal

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:25.620
to y over 12, so y is equal
to 20 over 15 times 12.

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:29.810
So that's 4 over 3,
so that's 16.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:32.380
So at our key moment in time,
these are the values that

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:34.160
we're going to end
up plugging in.

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:41.330
And also, dx dt is equal to 5.

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:42.691
x is being increased.

00:10:42.691 --> 00:10:42.752
Increased?

00:10:42.752 --> 00:10:49.970
Yeah x is, right, so as the foot
gets pulled away, x is

00:10:49.970 --> 00:10:50.730
getting bigger.

00:10:50.730 --> 00:10:53.063
So x is being increased
at 5 units per second.

00:10:53.063 --> 00:10:54.260
All right, so these are
all the things we're

00:10:54.260 --> 00:10:54.712
going to plug in.

00:10:54.712 --> 00:10:55.962
All right, good.

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:03.260
So now we are after dy dt at
this moment. and we don't

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:08.750
have, and we know dx dt.

00:11:08.750 --> 00:11:11.185
We don't have a direct
relationship between y and x,

00:11:11.185 --> 00:11:14.460
but do have a direct
relationship between y and d.

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:22.040
So if we got dd dt-- sorry--
dd dt, then we could get dy

00:11:22.040 --> 00:11:24.660
dt, and because of this
relationship,

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:26.450
we can get dd dt.

00:11:26.450 --> 00:11:26.720
All right.

00:11:26.720 --> 00:11:28.890
So let's start off
by doing that.

00:11:28.890 --> 00:11:30.470
So OK, so this is an identity.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.690
It holds always so we can
differentiate it.

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:34.600
And we're going to
differentiate it

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:36.020
with respect to t.

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:37.920
x and d are functions of t.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:38.090
So OK.

00:11:38.090 --> 00:11:42.500
So differentiating this
identity I get

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:50.090
2x times dx dt plus--

00:11:50.090 --> 00:11:54.440
well, OK, derivative of 144
with respect to t is 0--

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:56.890
is equal to--

00:11:56.890 --> 00:11:59.320
I guess I could expand this out,
but it's easier just to

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:02.760
use the chain rule right away--
so this is equal to 2

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:09.740
times 20 minus d times the
derivative of 20 minus d with

00:12:09.740 --> 00:12:16.270
respect to t, which
is minus dd dt.

00:12:16.270 --> 00:12:18.710
All right.

00:12:18.710 --> 00:12:21.770
I beg the gods of
math notation to

00:12:21.770 --> 00:12:24.710
forgive me for dd dt.

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:27.020
But, OK.

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:30.280
So, allright, so now,
this is always true.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.910
And what we want is the value
of dd dt at our particular

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:35.310
moment in time.

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:40.423
So at our particular moment in
time we have, well let's

00:12:40.423 --> 00:12:42.760
see,so OK, we have x, we have
the dx dt, and we have d.

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:47.030
So we can just plug all
those things in.

00:12:47.030 --> 00:12:50.030
So, at our moment, let me see
how I'm going to do this.

00:12:50.030 --> 00:12:52.200
I'll do it over here.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:13:06.790
At our moment, so 2x is 18
times dx dt is 5 equals 2

00:13:06.790 --> 00:13:17.620
times 20 minus d is 15
times minus dd dt.

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:21.500
And dd dt is what we're after.

00:13:21.500 --> 00:13:21.760
So OK.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:25.980
So divide 2 into this is 9.

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:34.490
45 divided by 15 is 3, so dd dt
is equal to minus 3 at the

00:13:34.490 --> 00:13:36.140
moment that we're
interested in.

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:36.480
All right.

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:37.800
Great.

00:13:37.800 --> 00:13:41.250
So now we have dd dt, and so
now we can go back to the

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:44.900
second relationship we have, the
one that relates d and y,

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:47.790
and we can do the
same thing here.

00:13:47.790 --> 00:13:52.240
We can take a derivative, use
the chain rule, use, and get a

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:57.160
relationship between dy
dt and d and dd dt.

00:13:57.160 --> 00:14:00.660
And then we'll be able to plug
in all these values we have

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:04.310
for our particular moment.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:06.530
So OK, so I think I'm
just going to

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:07.870
differentiate this straight.

00:14:07.870 --> 00:14:10.390
There are some simplifications
I could do first, but it'll

00:14:10.390 --> 00:14:12.770
work fine if we just
do it straight.

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:15.880
So OK, so I need to compute
the derivative.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:16.630
This is an identity.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.070
I can take its derivative, so I
differentiate the left hand

00:14:20.070 --> 00:14:28.270
side with respect to t, so I
get 20 over-- so this is a

00:14:28.270 --> 00:14:33.640
minus first power-- so I get
minus 20 over 20 minus d

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:35.590
quantity squared times--

00:14:35.590 --> 00:14:44.140
I need the derivative of the
bottom-- is minus dd dt.

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:55.150
And on the right hand side
I get dy dt over 12.

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:59.280
So I have this relationship
between d and y, I take its

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:02.230
derivative, now I have a
relationship that involves dy

00:15:02.230 --> 00:15:05.150
dt, which is the thing
that I'm after.

00:15:05.150 --> 00:15:07.290
So, whew.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:09.760
So now, I'm back at this
plugging in stage.

00:15:09.760 --> 00:15:13.470
So at our moment in time, I
know what d is, and I just

00:15:13.470 --> 00:15:17.420
figured out what dd dt is, so
I can just plug those values

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:21.050
in to figure out
what dy dt is.

00:15:21.050 --> 00:15:22.140
So OK, so let's do that.

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:25.570
So at this moment in
time we have--

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:28.220
so let me just multiply through
by the 12 and that

00:15:28.220 --> 00:15:34.510
will let us solve-- so we have
dy dt is equal to 12 times,

00:15:34.510 --> 00:15:45.050
well, so it's minus 20 over 15
squared, times minus, minus 3.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:47.150
Times 3.

00:15:47.150 --> 00:15:48.400
So this is--

00:15:51.110 --> 00:15:51.610
all right.

00:15:51.610 --> 00:15:53.470
Arithmetic.

00:15:53.470 --> 00:15:54.850
Not my favorite thing
in the world.

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:57.810
So we've got two 3's here.

00:15:57.810 --> 00:16:01.500
We're going to end up with a 5
in the denominator, and then

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:09.850
we've got 4 times minus 4, so
that's minus 16 over 5.

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:12.560
So.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:13.020
All right.

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:16.160
So that's the answer.

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:18.980
Let's remember what
we've done.

00:16:18.980 --> 00:16:23.210
So minus 16 over 5, that's
a negative number.

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:24.880
Why is it a negative number?

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:30.160
Well, as we pull this, the
bottom of this ladder here

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:34.680
away from the wall, the top of
the ladder is going to fall

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:36.970
downwards, it's going to get
closer to the ground.

00:16:36.970 --> 00:16:42.820
And y is the vertical distance
between the ground and the top

00:16:42.820 --> 00:16:43.250
of the ladder.

00:16:43.250 --> 00:16:46.220
So that's shrinking; y is
shrinking and should have a

00:16:46.220 --> 00:16:47.290
negative derivative.

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:48.150
OK.

00:16:48.150 --> 00:16:51.194
Negative derivative, minus 16
over 5 feet per second.

00:16:51.194 --> 00:16:55.330
So it would take, if this
instantaneous rate held up,

00:16:55.330 --> 00:16:56.750
which it won't in
this situation--

00:16:56.750 --> 00:16:59.760
if it held up it would take 5
seconds to get down, so it's

00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:01.060
not falling very quickly.

00:17:01.060 --> 00:17:01.440
OK.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:04.320
That seems about right.

00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:05.290
Anything else?

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:09.290
I guess we computed that dd
dt was also negative.

00:17:09.290 --> 00:17:12.370
Same thing here-- when you pull
this way, this length is

00:17:12.370 --> 00:17:14.860
going to shrink, so d is getting
smaller, so it has

00:17:14.860 --> 00:17:16.110
negative derivative.

00:17:18.600 --> 00:17:19.660
OK.

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:24.704
So at this moment in time, the
top of the ladder is falling--

00:17:24.704 --> 00:17:29.280
the thing we're interested in--
at exactly 16 over 5 feet

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:30.880
per second.

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:32.450
And we're all set.